<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-09-18T12:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-09-18T12:00:00-05:00" n="1267" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1267">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 763.72116/40</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to
                                the Ambassador in Germany</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GJW2" type="to"><hi rend="italic">Gerard</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <dateline>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-09-18T12:00:00-05:00">
                                <hi rend="italic">September 18, 1914, 12 noon</hi>.</date>
                        </dateline>
                        <p rend="center">[Telegram]</p>
                        <p>191. Just received telegram referring to dumdum bullets. While you could
                            not refuse to send specimens if requested the Government will of course
                            understand that no action will be taken by this Government <pb facs="1112" n="798" xml:id="pg_798"/> in the matter. The President’s
                            answer to the Emperor will cover all matters of this kind. He hears
                            whatever is said but does not discuss the merits of the controversy and
                            your action in refusing to be drawn into the discussion of such
                            questions is approved.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <persName corresp="#p_BWJ1">
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">W.J.Bryan</hi>
                                </persName>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>